I think you're close, but I think it's actually the opposite.

+theory

-theory


The title is , without the word SCP before it, but the number is an SCP number. 5919 doesn't make sense as an apartment number, given the size of the building depicted. So what I think is going on is the opposite. The artist's creation does exactly the opposite of what you theorized, I think, preventing any importance being given to it, rather than giving itself importance.

I think it's an apartment whose only anomalous property is that you can't describe it as anything more elaborate than a simple apartment. Even describing this anomalous property isn't possible, or it would be in the article.

The MCD tried to do an exhibition of this renowned artist's latest and greatest work, but the properties of the apartment made it impossible for them to even explain what made the work notable enough to view.

The complete and utter failure of his ambition perhaps then drove Andrej to commit suicide.

Notably, though, both the fact that the Foundation documented it as an SCP and MC it in any way.




Very clever SCP. I really enjoyed working it out. I'm still wondering if there are any implications I missed.
Edit:

+missed

-missed


There's a three-year gap between when he created the apartment, and when MCD's invitation that caused him to commit suicide.

So, next theory is that MCD managed to not only discover the apartment, but managed, by simply attaching their name to it, managed to successfully advertise the apartment to some of their high-profile clients. The apartment's complete inability to be referred to as anything exceptional could certainly be very useful. And this exploitation, this perversion of Andrej's intent to create something truly unexceptional is what drove him to suicide, I theorize.

I think that there might be more to it, though. The truly spartan interior of the apartment does make me wonder if maybe the anomaly actually prevents you from decorating it.

It states that the last resident moved out in 2018, and nobody else has moved in. The containment procedures state that nobody is prevented from moving in, so it is probably the anomalous property of the apartment that has prevented it from being rented out. Presumably the last resident was Andrej, as even saying that he lived in it would be a way of advertising it.

It is interesting that the properties of the apartment don't prevent the Foundation from using the standard format. It even has special containment procedures. Given the redundant descriptions of the caretaker, I think it is implied that the caretaker is an SCP asset, but they can't actually write that out.

Thinking about it, the fact that the Object Class is N/A is almost certainly an effect of the apartment, as even a Safe designation would imply the apartment has anomalous properties, and the apartment suppresses any suggestion that it is anything other than mundane. Probably the Foundation would prefer to give it a Safe or Euclid designation. As the effect would be very quickly realized by anyone attempting to  a potential tenant on the property.

actually the luggage stand kind of stands out. This apartment is being used as more of a hotel room, isn't it? That makes much more sense, and would be much easier to cover up.








